PHY 162a Note 1 - Motion Equation

Notes

Euler–Lagrange equation:

∂L∂qα−ddt∂L∂q˙α=0

For two independent systems A and B

Ltot=LA+LB

and LA , LB should be independent from each other.

Also, the Lagrange funtions of the system can difference to each other with and only with a funtion of total derivative of time(or constant).

Inertial frame of reference

Space is uniform and isotropy in this frame. Time is uniform.

Thus, free particle in inertial grame of reference:

L=L(v2)

according to Euler-Lagrange equation

ddt∂L∂v=0

which means

v=const

In two arbi Inertial frame of reference:

r=r′+Vt t=t′

L of free particle

L=∑amava22

L of particle systems

L=∑amava22−U(r1,r2,…)

The motion equation:

ddt∂L∂va=∂L∂ra Fa=madvadt=−∂U∂ra

if we use general coordinate q

L=12aik(q)q˙iq˙k−U(q)

where Einstein sum applied

In external field

L=12aik(q)q˙iq˙k−U(q,t)

In uniform external field

U=−F⋅r

Problem Set I.

Give the Lagrange function of the following system in uniform gravity field with g

1.1

Position of particle 1

q

1.2

A flat plate of mass $ m_2 $ has a pivot point on which a small mass m1 can slide freely. The mass m1 can move along a straight horizontal line on the surface of the plate $ m_2 $ .

1.3

There is a planar pendulum whose suspension point:

a. Moves along the vertical direction in uniform circular motion with angular frequency γ (see System3(a));

b. Oscillates horizontally within the plane of the pendulum according to the law acos⁡γt ;

c. Oscillates vertically according to the law acos⁡γt .

1.4

In the mechanical system shown in System4, the point mass m2 moves along the vertical axis, while the entire system rotates about this axis with a constant angular velocity Ω .

.

Solution

1.1

The cartisan position of the particle 1 and 2:

r1=(l1sin⁡φ1,l1cos⁡φ1) r2=(l1sin⁡φ1+l2sin⁡φ2,l1cos⁡φ1+l2cos⁡φ2)

Then the Lagrange:

L1=12m1[(dl1sin⁡φ1dt)2+(dl1cos⁡φ1dt)2]+m1gl1cos⁡φ1=12m1l12φ˙12+m1gl1cos⁡φ1 L2=12m2[(dl1sin⁡φ1+l2sin⁡φ2dt)2+(dl1cos⁡φ1+l2cos⁡φ2dt)2]+m2g(l1cos⁡φ1+l2cos⁡φ2)=12m2(l12φ˙12+l22φ˙22+2l1l2φ˙1φ˙2cos⁡φ1cos⁡φ2+2l1l2φ˙1φ˙2sin⁡φ1sin⁡φ2)+m2g(l1cos⁡φ1+l2cos⁡φ2)=12m2(l12φ˙12+l22φ˙22+2l1l2φ˙1φ˙2cos⁡(φ1−φ2))+m2g(l1cos⁡φ1+l2cos⁡φ2)

Total Lagranfe:

L=L1+L2=12m1l12φ˙12+m1gl1cos⁡φ1+12m2(l12φ˙12+l22φ˙22+2l1l2φ˙1φ˙2cos⁡(φ1−φ2))+m2g(l1cos⁡φ1+l2cos⁡φ2)

1.2

The cartisan position of the particle 1 and 2:

r1=(x,0) r2=(x+lsin⁡φ,lcos⁡φ) L1=12m1x˙2 L2=12m2[x˙2+2lx˙φ˙cosφ+l2φ˙2cos2⁡φ+l2φ˙2sin2⁡φ]+m2glcos⁡φ=12m2[x˙2+2lx˙φ˙cosφ+l2φ˙2]+m2glcos⁡φ L=L1+L2=12m1x˙2+12m2[x˙2+2lx˙φ˙cosφ+l2φ˙2]+m2glcos⁡φ

1.3

(a)

position of particle

r=(acos⁡γt+lsin⁡φ,asin⁡γt+lcos⁡φ) L=12m[(dacos⁡γt+lsin⁡φdt)2+(dasin⁡γt+lcos⁡φdt)2]+mg(asin⁡γt+lcos⁡φ)=12m[(−aγsin⁡γt+lφ˙cos⁡φ)2+(aγcos⁡γt−lφ˙sin⁡φ)2]+mg(asin⁡γt+lcos⁡φ)=12m[a2γ2−2alγφ˙sin⁡γtcos⁡φ−2alγφ˙sin⁡φcos⁡γt+l2φ˙2]+mg(asin⁡γt+lcos⁡φ)=12m[l2φ˙−2laγφ˙sin⁡(γt+φ)]+mglcos⁡φ

Here we ignore the time dependent and constant terms.

(b)

position of particle

r=(acos⁡γt+lsin⁡φ,lcos⁡φ) L=12m[(dacos⁡γt+lsin⁡φdt)2+(dlcos⁡φdt)2]+mglcos⁡φ=12m[(−aγsin⁡γt+lφ˙cos⁡φ)2+(−lφ˙sin⁡φ)2]+mglcos⁡φ=12m[−2alγφ˙sin⁡γtcos⁡φ+l2φ˙2]+mglcos⁡φ

In origin book, the author added a total derivative to simplify the function

L=12m[−2alγφ˙sin⁡γtcos⁡φ+l2φ˙2]+mglcos⁡φ=12m[−2alγφ˙sin⁡γtcos⁡φ+l2φ˙2]+mglcos⁡φ+ddt(mlaγsin⁡φsin⁡γt)=12m[−2alγφ˙sin⁡γtcos⁡φ+l2φ˙2]+mglcos⁡φ+mlaγφ˙cos⁡φsin⁡γt+mlaγ2sin⁡φcos⁡γt=12ml2φ2+mlaγ2sin⁡φcos⁡γt+mglcos⁡φ

©

By replacing acos⁡γt in x direction with acos⁡γt in y direction

L=12ml2φ2+mlaγ2cos⁡φcos⁡γt+mglcos⁡φ

1.4

position of particle 1.1, 1.2, 2

r11=(asin⁡θcos⁡Ωt,acos⁡θ,asin⁡θsin⁡Ωt)r11=(−asin⁡θcos⁡Ωt,acos⁡θ,−asin⁡θsin⁡Ωt) r2=(0,2acos⁡θ,0) (dr1dt)2=(dasin⁡θcos⁡Ωtdt)2+(dacos⁡θdt)2+(dasin⁡θsin⁡Ωtdt)2=a2θ˙2+a2Ω2sin2⁡θ (dr2dt)2=(d2acos⁡θdt)2=4a2θ˙2sin2θ L=m1(a2θ˙2+a2Ω2sin2⁡θ)+2m2(a2θ˙2sin2θ)+2m1g(acos⁡θ)+2m2g(acos⁡θ)
